.TH PHASORSTD_TYPE 3 "January 2026" "Phasor 3.3.0" "Phasor Standard Library 2.0.0"
.SH NAME
phasorstd_type \- Phasor type conversion and JSON functions
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
.B using("stdtype");
.PP
.B to_int(value)
.B to_float(value)
.B to_string(value)
.B to_bool(value)
.B from_json(json_string)
.fi
.SH FUNCTIONS
.TP
.BR to_int (value)
Convert a value to an integer.
.RS
.PP
.B Arguments:
.RS
.IP \fBvalue\fR 12
Value to convert (any type)
.RE
.PP
.B Conversion Rules:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Integer: Returns unchanged
.IP \(bu 2
Float: Truncates to integer (rounds toward zero)
.IP \(bu 2
String: Parses as integer, returns 0 if invalid
.IP \(bu 2
Boolean: true → 1, false → 0
.IP \(bu 2
Other: Returns 0
.RE
.PP
.B Returns:
64-bit signed integer (int64)
.RE
.PP
.TP
.BR to_float (value)
Convert a value to a floating-point number.
.RS
.PP
.B Arguments:
.RS
.IP \fBvalue\fR 12
Value to convert (any type)
.RE
.PP
.B Conversion Rules:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Float: Returns unchanged
.IP \(bu 2
Integer: Converts to float
.IP \(bu 2
String: Parses as float (using standard conversion)
.IP \(bu 2
Boolean: true → 1.0, false → 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
Other: Implementation-defined
.RE
.PP
.B Returns:
64-bit floating-point number (double)
.RE
.PP
.TP
.BR to_string (value)
Convert a value to its string representation.
.RS
.PP
.B Arguments:
.RS
.IP \fBvalue\fR 12
Value to convert (any type)
.RE
.PP
.B Conversion Rules:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
String: Returns unchanged
.IP \(bu 2
Integer: Decimal representation
.IP \(bu 2
Float: Decimal representation with implementation-defined precision
.IP \(bu 2
Boolean: "true" or "false"
.IP \(bu 2
Null: "null"
.IP \(bu 2
Struct: JSON string representation of the struct
.IP \(bu 2
Array: JSON string representation of the array
.RE
.PP
.B Returns:
String representation of the value. For structs and arrays, returns a JSON string.
.RE
.PP
.TP
.BR to_bool (value)
Convert a value to a boolean.
.RS
.PP
.B Arguments:
.RS
.IP \fBvalue\fR 12
Value to convert (any type)
.RE
.PP
.B Conversion Rules:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Boolean: Returns unchanged
.IP \(bu 2
Integer: 0 → false, non-zero → true
.IP \(bu 2
Float: 0.0 → false, non-zero → true
.IP \(bu 2
String: empty → false, non-empty → true
.IP \(bu 2
Null: false
.IP \(bu 2
Other: Implementation-defined (typically true)
.RE
.PP
.B Returns:
Boolean true or false
.RE
.PP
.TP
.BR from_json (json_string)
Parse a JSON string into a Phasor value.
.RS
.PP
.B Arguments:
.RS
.IP \fBjson_string\fR 12
A string containing valid JSON data
.RE
.PP
.B Description:
Parses the given JSON string and returns the corresponding Phasor value.
JSON objects become structs, JSON arrays become Phasor arrays, and JSON primitives become null, bool, int, float, or string as appropriate.
.PP
.B Returns:
A Phasor value (struct, array, or primitive) representing the parsed JSON data.
.PP
.B Errors:
Throws a runtime error if the argument is not a string or if the JSON is malformed.
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.B Integer Conversion
.PP
.nf
.RS
include_stdtype();

puts(to_int(42));        // 42
puts(to_int(3.14));      // 3
puts(to_int(3.99));      // 3 (truncates)
puts(to_int("123"));     // 123
puts(to_int("abc"));     // 0 (invalid)
puts(to_int(true));      // 1
puts(to_int(false));     // 0
.RE
.fi
.PP
.B Float Conversion
.PP
.nf
.RS
puts(to_float(42));      // 42.0
puts(to_float(3.14));    // 3.14
puts(to_float("2.718")); // 2.718
puts(to_float(true));    // 1.0
.RE
.fi
.PP
.B String Conversion
.PP
.nf
.RS
puts(to_string(42));     // "42"
puts(to_string(3.14));   // "3.14" (or similar)
puts(to_string(true));   // "true"
puts(to_string(false));  // "false"
puts(to_string(null));   // "null"

var person = { name: "Alice", age: 30 };
puts(to_string(person)); // "{"name":"Alice","age":30}"

var colors = ["red", "green", "blue"];
puts(to_string(colors)); // "["red","green","blue"]"

var x = 100;
var msg = concat("Value: ", to_string(x));
puts(msg);  // "Value: 100"
.RE
.fi
.PP
.B Boolean Conversion
.PP
.nf
.RS
puts(to_bool(1));        // true
puts(to_bool(0));        // false
puts(to_bool(-5));       // true
puts(to_bool(0.0));      // false
puts(to_bool(0.1));      // true
puts(to_bool(""));       // false
puts(to_bool("hello"));  // true
puts(to_bool("0"));      // true (non-empty string)
.RE
.fi
.PP
.B JSON Parsing
.PP
.nf
.RS
include_stdtype();

var json_str = "{"name":"John","age":30,"tags":["dev","ops"]}";
var data = from_json(json_str);

puts(data.name);   // "John"
puts(data.age);    // 30
puts(data.tags.0); // "dev"
puts(data.tags.1); // "ops"

// Round-trip JSON
var original = { a: 1, b: [2, 3] };
var serialized = to_string(original);
var restored = from_json(serialized);
puts(restored.a);        // 1
puts(restored.b.1);      // 3
.RE
.fi
.PP
.B Parsing User Input
.PP
.nf
.RS
include_stdio();
include_stdtype();

puts("Enter a number:");
var input = gets();
var number = to_int(input);

if (number == 0 && input != "0") {
    puts("Invalid number entered");
} else {
    putf("You entered: %d", number);
}
.RE
.fi
.PP
.B Type-Safe Calculations
.PP
.nf
.RS
fn safe_divide(a, b) {
    var dividend = to_float(a);
    var divisor = to_float(b);
    
    if (divisor == 0.0) {
        error("Division by zero");
    }
    
    return dividend / divisor;
}

var result = safe_divide("10", "3");
puts(result);  // 3.333...
.RE
.fi
.PP
.B Configuration Parsing with JSON
.PP
.nf
.RS
// Assume config.json contains: { "timeout": 30, "debug": true }
var config_str = read_file("config.json");
var config = from_json(config_str);

if (to_bool(config.debug)) {
    puts("Debug mode enabled");
}
var timeout_ms = to_int(config.timeout) * 1000;
.RE
.fi
.SH NOTES
.IP \(bu 2
Integer conversion truncates floating-point values (does not round)
.IP \(bu 2
String-to-number conversion returns 0 for invalid strings
.IP \(bu 2
Boolean conversion of strings only checks if empty, not content
.IP \(bu 2
Type conversion functions never throw errors (except \fBfrom_json\fR)
.IP \(bu 2
Float precision may vary in string conversion
.IP \(bu 2
Very large integers may lose precision when converted to float
.IP \(bu 2
\fBto_string\fR on structs/arrays produces JSON that is compatible with \fBfrom_json\fR
.IP \(bu 2
\fBfrom_json\fR requires a valid JSON string; malformed input causes a runtime error
.IP \(bu 2
JSON objects become structs; JSON arrays become Phasor arrays. Nested combinations are fully supported.
.SH TYPE SYSTEM
Phasor supports the following types:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
.B null
\- Null/undefined value
.IP \(bu 2
.B bool
\- Boolean (true/false)
.IP \(bu 2
.B int
\- 64-bit signed integer
.IP \(bu 2
.B float
\- 64-bit floating-point (IEEE 754 double)
.IP \(bu 2
.B string
\- UTF-8 text string
.IP \(bu 2
.B struct
\- User-defined composite type (JSON object compatible)
.IP \(bu 2
.B array
\- Ordered list of values (JSON array compatible)
.RE
.SH BEST PRACTICES
.IP \(bu 2
Always validate converted values when parsing user input
.IP \(bu 2
Use \fBto_string()\fR to concatenate non-string values or to serialize structs/arrays to JSON
.IP \(bu 2
Be aware of precision loss when converting large integers to float
.IP \(bu 2
Check for zero before division when converting strings to numbers
.IP \(bu 2
Use explicit conversion rather than relying on implicit coercion
.IP \(bu 2
Use \fBfrom_json()\fR to parse structured data from external sources
.IP \(bu 2
Remember that \fBfrom_json()\fR can throw errors; wrap in try-catch if needed
